english:
  title: Seven Songs of the Eastern Capital
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I. The Song of Hoesoᴇ

    In the ninth year of King Yuri's reign, the six districts were named and divided in two. Two royal daughters each led the women of their districts, divided into teams. From the fifteenth day of the seventh month, they gathered each dawn in the great courtyard to spin hemp, working until deep night. When the fifteenth day of the eighth month came, they compared their work—the losing side prepared wine and food to thank the winners. Then came song and dance and celebration, called the Great Merriment. A woman from the losing side rose to dance, sighing "Hoeso, Hoeso"—such mournful, delicate tones. Later generations took that voice and made a song, naming it the Song of Hoeso.

    Hoeso, Hoeso—
    West wind sweeps the broad courtyard,
    Bright moon fills the painted hall.
    The royal daughter sits spinning at her wheel,
    The women of six districts cluster like bamboo.

    Your basket brims while mine stands empty,
    We raise our cups, tease and jest with laughter.
    One woman's sigh stirs a thousand households to diligence,
    Even sitting here, the four directions grow eager at their looms.

    Though the Great Merriment loses courtly grace,
    It surpasses the river games and their cacophony.

    II. The Song of Sorrowful Sigh

    In the first year of King Silseong's reign, Prince Malsa-hun, son of King Naemul, was sent as hostage to Japan. In the eleventh year, his brother Bokhaᴇ was sent as hostage to Goguryeo. When King Nulji ascended the throne, longing to see his brothers, he sought a skilled orator. Park Je-sang, prefect of Salpyang, was recommended. Je-sang went to Goguryeo and brought back Bokhaᴇ, then crossed the sea to Japan, deceived the Japanese king, and secretly brought Malsa-hun home. The king rejoiced greatly, ordering the six districts to welcome them from afar. When the brothers met, they grasped hands and wept, feasted together in great celebration. The king composed a song to express his joy, which came to be called the Song of Sorrowful Sigh.

    The flower of the Common Thistle, blown by wind, falls to the Mulberry Land,
    The Mulberry Land stretches ten thousand leagues across whale-dark waves—
    Should we send letters, who would carry them?
    The flower of the Common Thistle returns on the wind to Chicken Forest,
    The spring colors of Chicken Forest embrace the twin palaces,
    Such is the depth of fraternal joy.

    III. The Song of Chirseul Ridge

    When Park Je-sang returned from Goguryeo, he went directly to Japan without seeing his wife. She pursued him to Yat Stream and saw him already on the boat. She called out and wept bitterly, but Je-sang only waved his hand and departed. After Je-sang died in Japan, his wife, overcome with longing, took their three daughters up Chirseul Ridge, gazed toward Japan, wept until she died, and became the guardian deity of the ridge.

    From Chirseul Ridge's height, gazing toward Japan,
    The sea stretches to heaven's edge, boundless, unending—
    When my husband left, he only waved his hand,
    Living or dead? All word has ceased.

    This endless parting—will death or life ever bring us face to face?
    Calling to heaven, she turned to stone at Wuchang,
    Her fierce spirit soars through a thousand years in the blue void.

    IV. The Song of the Dreadful Day

    In the tenth year of King Joji's reign, the king was playing at the Spring Heaven Pavilion when an old man emerged from the pond bearing a scroll. On its outer face was written: "If you open it, two die. If you don't, one dies." The king said, "Better one should die than two." But the court astrologer replied, "The two are the common people; the one is the king." In fear, the king opened it and read: "Shoot at the qin case."

    Entering the palace, he found the qin case leaning against the wall. He shot it and it fell—inside was a monk from the inner chambers. The queen had admitted him, and they had conspired to murder the king. The queen was executed. From that time forward, on the first days of each zodiacal month—the rat, boar, and horse days—the people avoided all activities, calling these the Dreadful Days. Later, the sixteenth was added as the Crow's Day, when they offered glutinous rice in sacrifice.

    Dreadful, sorrowful—
    The kingdom almost fell that day!
    In the silk-curtained chamber the qin lies overturned,
    The fair queen could not grow old with her lord.

    Sorrow, sorrow—
    Without the spirit's warning, what would have happened?
    Because the spirit revealed all, the realm stands secure!

    V. The Song of Yang Mountain

    Kim Heum-un was the eighth-generation descendant of King Naemul. In his youth he studied under the Hwarang master Mun-no. In the sixth year of the Yonghuei era, King Taejong appointed him Commander of the Warrior Band to attack Baekje, and they camped below Yang Mountain. When Baekje discovered this, they attacked at night. At dawn's edge, the enemy scaled the walls. Our army panicked as arrows fell like rain. Heum-un, mounted, waited for the enemy. His attendants urged retreat, but he drew his sword against them, then charged forward with the commanders. Fighting fiercely, he killed several before falling. When Commander Bo-yong-na heard of Heum-un's death, he wept and said, "His bone rank is noble, his station high, yet he kept his honor unto death. How much more should I, whose life brings no benefit and whose death brings no loss?" He charged the enemy and died. People composed the Song of Yang Mountain to lament them.

    The enemy comes like ravenous wild boar,
    Devouring our borderlands.
    Magnificent flower-youths of the Hwarang,
    With hearts devoted to the nation, no other thought.

    Grasping spears, bidding farewell to wife and child,
    Drinking from mountain springs, eating rice balls,
    The enemy breaches the walls in darkness,
    The noble soul flies on the sword's point.

    Looking back at Yang Mountain's clouds,
    Arching, radiant with rainbow light—
    Alas, you four heroes!
    Yet you remain the mighty-hearted ones.
    Through a thousand autumns as spirits of valor,
    Tasting together the wine of sacrifice.

    VI. The Song of the Mortar

    Master Baek-gyeol of a hundred patches lost his name to history. He lived below Wolf Mountain, so poor his clothes were patched a hundred times, like quail feathers hanging thick. From youth he admired the wisdom of Yeong-gyae-gi. He carried a qin wherever he went, expressing through its strings all joy and anger, sorrow and delight, all discontent. One year as winter approached, neighbors began threshing grain. His wife, hearing the pestle's sound, sighed, "All have grain but us—how shall we survive the year?" The master looked to heaven and spoke: "Life and death are fate; fortune rests in heaven's hands. What comes cannot be refused, what goes cannot be pursued. Why do you grieve? I shall play you the pestle's song to comfort you."

    He played his qin, mimicking the pestle's sound. From this came the Song of the Mortar:

    The eastern house grinds millet and rice,
    The western house pounds winter clothes.
    East and west, pestle and mortar sound—
    The year's provisions overflow and overflow,

    Our cellar lacks a single measure,
    Our chest holds not one length of silk.
    Hanging patches, wild greens in a bowl—
    Yet Yeong-gyae-gi's joy suffices for warmth!

    Wife, dear wife, do not sorrow!
    Fortune lies in heaven—why seek it by force?
    Curled on hard ground, drinking water, arm for pillow,
    There is supreme taste in this.
    I am Yang Hong, you are Meng Guang—heaven's matched pair!

    VII. The Song of Hwang Chang-rang

    Hwang Chang-rang—what age he came from, none can say. Legend tells that as a boy of eight, he conspired with Silla's king to strike back at Baekje. He went to Baekje's market to perform sword dances. Crowds gathered thick as walls to watch. The Baekje king heard and summoned him to the palace to dance. There, Chang-rang thrust and killed the king. Later generations carved masks in his image, and his dance is performed alongside the Dance of Cheo-yong. Yet the histories record nothing of this. Some say it was not the Pure Youth but a corruption of the name Official Chang, though such theories cannot be trusted. Yet watching the dance now—the spinning, the turning glances, the sudden flashing movements—even now it bristles with living breath. The dance has rhythm but no words, so I compose verses for it:

    There stands a boy, barely more than a child,
    Hardly three feet tall, yet spirited and bold.
    King Qi of my lifetime was my teacher—
    For the nation's honor, my heart knows no doubt.

    When the sword's edge presses the neck, the legs do not tremble,
    When the blade's point marks the heart, the eyes do not flinch.
    Once the deed is done, lightly he departs his dance,
    As if he could leap the great mountains, cross the northern sea.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Common Thistle (常棣) is used in the Classic of Poetry as a metaphor for brotherhood, its flowers clustered close together.
  - key: ''
    value: The Wuchang Stone refers to the Stone of the Gazing Wife in Chinese legend—a woman who watched daily from a mountain for her distant husband's return, until she herself turned to stone.
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yeong-gyae-gi was an ancient sage who lived in poverty but sang and danced in joy, saying: ''I am glad to be born human, glad to be born male, glad to have lived long.'''
  - key: ''
    value: Yang Hong and Meng Guang were a virtuous couple of the Later Han dynasty, who lived humbly together in perfect contentment.
  - key: ''
    value: King Qi (王氣) was a child warrior of the Spring and Autumn period who died fighting for his state.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Dreadful Days' (怛忉日) refer to unlucky days when people avoided work and activity, established after the assassination plot was revealed.
